  "summary": "This paper presents a novel multi-agent linear stochastic approximation algorithm driven by Markovian noise and general consensus-type interaction, where each agent evolves according to its local stochastic approximation process and depends on the information from its neighbors. The interconnection structure among the agents is described by a time-varying directed graph. The paper derives finite-time bounds on the mean-square error for a uniformly strongly connected graph sequence whose associated interaction matrices are stochastic.",
  "main_review": "The paper is technically sound and provides a thorough analysis of the proposed algorithm. The authors have adequately addressed the challenges of removing the assumption of doubly stochastic matrices in the analysis of distributed stochastic approximation algorithms. The paper provides a general analysis methodology and results that subsume the existing finite-time analyses for single-timescale distributed linear stochastic approximation and TD learning as special cases. The push-based distributed stochastic approximation algorithm is well-motivated and its finite-time performance bound is well-established. However, the paper could benefit from a clearer explanation of the practical implications of the proposed algorithm and the potential applications in multi-agent reinforcement learning.",
  "limitations_and_societal_impact": "The authors have adequately addressed the limitations of their work, including the fact that the algorithm may not converge to the policies that maximize the average of the utility functions of the agents. They have also discussed the potential negative societal impacts of their work, including the possibility of uni-directional communication in realistic networks. However, the paper could benefit from a more detailed discussion of the potential societal implications of the proposed algorithm and its potential applications.",
  "rating": "9: Very Strong Accept"
}

